<hl>
<seg id=1> Japanese Prime Minister Hopes Miyazawa Will Remain in Office to Promote Economic Recovery Plan </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Reuters, Tokyo, Telegram) Japanese Finance Minister Miyazawa was pressured to remain in office yesterday. </seg>
<seg id=3> He had announced last week that he intended to resign soon. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The departure or retention of Miyazawa casts a shadow over the coalition government of the Liberal Democratic Party led by Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi and the Liberal Party led by Ichiro Kozawa. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> The coalition government became unstable after a difference in views surfaced among senior officials over the issue of whether or not the cabinet posts filled by the Liberty Party were part of an agreement between the parties. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> It had been widely rumored that Naeda, secretary general of the Liberal Party, would assume the post following the resignation of Miyazawa. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Miyazawa stated last Friday that he may resign by the end of the year. However, he did not give an exact date. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> He said at a press meeting: "I can't say when" </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> It is expected that he will stay on as finance minister until the end of the two-week Diet Special Conference. </seg>
<seg id=10> The Diet Conference will close on December 14. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Suzuki, vice cabinet secretary of Keizo Obuchi, told NHK Television that he believes that the prime minister wants the 79-year-old Miyazawa to stay. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> Suzuki said: "I think (Obuchi) privately wants him to stay in office to promote his economic recovery plan." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> Obuchi will meet with Miyazawa face-to-face. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=14> He said: "Given his capabilities, it would not be easy to find someone to replace him. </seg>
<seg id=15> As for myself, I hope he will stay on to vitalize the national economy." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=16> Obuchi's public comment on the departure of Miyazawa is that he saw the related report and he is going to have a discussion with the finance minister.  </seg>
</p>
